{
  "doc_id": "29611",
  "text": "The greater prognostic value of SPECT in women compared with men, as seen in our study, has not previously been reported. Prior studies even show that women have a slightly higher event rate than men after normal SPECT [CITATION_1] . These studies are predominantly performed in large clinics outside the Netherlands. Our results may be more representative for clinics in the Netherlands. Research in the Leiden University Medical Centre showed a worse prognosis of MACE in 5.9 % of patients [CITATION_2] . This study, however, was performed in a higher risk population and with a broader definition of MACE. The worse prognosis in men is an important finding for the daily practice in our hospital and in comparable clinics. Clinicians should be more careful in interpreting normal SPECT in men. Unlike our results, prior studies show a higher event rate in AF patients after normal SPECT than in non-AF patients [CITATION_3] . These studies defined AF only by findings on the baseline resting ECG. Both paroxysmal and persistent AF are known to have increased risk of developing MACE [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . Therefore, we also included patients with a prior history of AF to analyse the NPVof SPECT in AF patients. Our study is the first to show that the prognosis of normal SPECT in AF patients (on baseline resting ECG and prior history) is comparable with that of non-AF patients.",
